Introduction ¶

Data Source ¶

The dataset is taken from Kaggle Repository at https://www.kaggle.com/sakshigoyal7/credit-card-customers.

Credit Card Customers.(2020).BankChurners [Data File]. Retrieved from https://www.kaggle.com/sakshigoyal7/credit-card-customers

Dataset Details ¶

I will use Credit Card Customers dataset from Kaggle Repository for this project and there is only one csv file named BankChurners.csv. In this dataset, each row represents customer with unique ID and each column contains features or attributes of customers. The dataset is about credit card services of a bank, and purpose of it is to predict and to know the disappointed customers and to act proactively upon it.

Dataset Features ¶

In this dataset there are 10127 rows and 22 features, out of which we will only use 8 features and (number of rows) rows.

Table¶

Serial Number Name Of Features Datatype Units Brief Description
1 Attrition Flag object - Existing Customer, Attrited Customer
2 Customer Age int64 - Ages are in 26 to 73 bracket
3 Gender object - Defines Male or Female
4 Dependent count int64 - Number of dependents on an individual, is between 0 and 5.
5 Education Level object Unknown College, Doctorate, Graduate, High School, Post Graduate, Uneducated, Unknown
6 Marital Status object Unknown Whether an individual is Divorced, Married, Single, Unknown
7 Income Category object Unknown Defines income bracket-+120k, 40k-60k, 60k-80k,80k-120k,<40k, Unknown
8 Card Category object - Types of card-Blue, Gold, Platinum, Silver
9 Avg_Utilization_Ratio float64 - Mean of utilization ratio of customers

Target Feature¶

Our target feature is Customer_Age, which is a continuous feature.

Goals and Objectives¶

Our objective is to investigate the dataset and gain insights for better understanding the business situations.

Data Exploration and Visualization¶

This is a step, where we can actually play with our dataset as before we only cleanse it to to its level.

Univariate Visualization¶

Let's visualize the customer based on their income brackets.

In [12]:
display(HTML('<b>Figure 3: Bar Chart Of Income Category</b>'))
matplt.figure(figsize = (10, 5))
sb.countplot(x = 'Income_Category',data = dataframe2,order = dataframe2['Income_Category'].value_counts().index)
matplt.show();
Figure 3: Bar Chart Of Income Category

From Figure 3, we can say that most of our customers are from less than 40k bracket, then followed by 40k-60k and 80k-120k bracket respectively.

Now will have a look on Bar Plot of Gender.

In [13]:
matplt.figure(figsize = (10, 5))
sb.countplot(dataframe2['Gender']).set_title('Figure 4: Bar Plot of Gender', fontsize = 18)
matplt.show();

From Figure 4, we can deduce that our clientele is dominated by female customers than the male customers. The number of female customers add upto around 2700.

Bivariate Visualizaion¶

Let's get Bar plot of Attrition_Flag with Gender category.

In [14]:

Figure 5 clearly shows that females are more not only in our customer base but also in attrition list.

After having insights on customer, lets look, which gender uses our our credit card service more.

In [15]:
sb.boxplot(dataframe2['Gender'], dataframe2['Avg_Utilization_Ratio']);
matplt.title('Figure 6: Boxplot of Utilization by Gender', fontsize = 15)
matplt.show();

From the above box plot, we can easily conclude that customers, who are male has less average utilization ratio. As the female customers are more, there utilization ratio is also more.

Multivariate Visualization¶

Let's plot a boxplot of Gender breakdown by Attrition and Utilization

In [16]:
sb.boxplot(dataframe2['Attrition_Flag'],dataframe2['Avg_Utilization_Ratio'],hue=dataframe2['Gender'])
matplt.title('Figure 7: Boxplot of Gender breakdown by Attrition_Flag and Avg_Utilization_Ratio', fontsize=15)
matplt.show();

From Figure 7, we can deduce that customers, who are male have lesser utilization ratio and lesser tendency to leave the bank.

Lets plot and see how dependent count and age affect the attrition levels.

In [17]:
sb.barplot(x="Dependent_count", y="Customer_Age", hue="Attrition_Flag", data=dataframe2).set_title('Figure 8: Plot with Number of Dependents and Age', fontsize = 18)
matplt.show();

From the above figure, we can see that people with no dependency are tend to leave more than having dependency. People, who have dependency have the sort same level of existing and attrited customer.

In [18]:
sb.boxplot(dataframe2['Card_Category'],dataframe2['Customer_Age'],hue=dataframe2['Attrition_Flag'])
matplt.title('Figure 9: Boxplot of Card Category breakdown by Gender and Age', fontsize=15)
matplt.show();

From Figure 9, we can see that people, who own Platinum cards, tend to stay more than the owners of Gold cards and Silver cards. And Blue card owners have the same proportion of active and attrited customers.

Summary and Conclusion¶

In our investigation, we found that most of our customers are from less than 40k income bracket and most of the customers use Blue cards. Owners of Gold cards and Blue cards tend to leave the bank more than that of other cards. People with no dependency are tend to leave more, may be because the service bank is decent but rate of interest is bit high. Bank's customer base has more female customers than male customers, and which explains why they have more utilization. However, most of the people, who leave the bank, are females.
